    </p> <p data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"top-margins">
      For example, let=E2=80=99s calculate the median of the following data=
 set: 3, 5, 7, 8, 9 and 12. Because this sample contains 8 observations, th=
e median is the mean of the sorted that occupy the 6/2 =3D 3rd and (6+2)/2 =
=3D 4th positions. These correspond to 7 and 8, respectively. The median=E2=
=80=94as the mean of these two values=E2=80=94equals 7.5 or (7 + 8)/2.
    </p> <img data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" loading=3D"lazy" alt=3D"Median numbers w=
hen input is even." src=3D"https://statisticscalculators.com/_assets/images=
/mmm-03-desktop.png"> <p data-v-60ddaa04=3D"">Regardless of whether the tot=
al number of values in a data sample is odd or even, an equal number of obs=
ervations lie above and below the median. In addition, a data sample can on=
ly have one median.</p> <h4 data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"steps h6">
      Steps for Calculating the Median
    </h4> <p data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"bottom-margin-16">
      This measure of central tendency is slightly more difficult to find t=
han the other two. We break it down into simple steps to help you calculate=
 it. And you can use the Mean, Median, and Mode Calculator to verify the ob=
tained result.
    </p> <p data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"bottom-margins">
      There are two steps for calculating the median:
    </p> <ol data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"mean-median-mode-ol"><li data-v-=
60ddaa04=3D"">Sort the values into ascending or descending order.</li> <li =
data-v-60ddaa04=3D"">
        Determine the number of observations (n)
        <ul data-v-60ddaa04=3D""><li data-v-60ddaa04=3D"">If the sample siz=
e is odd, the median is the middle value and occupies (n + 1)/2 position.</=
li> <li data-v-60ddaa04=3D"">If the sample size is even, the median is the =
average of the two middle values that occupy the n/2 and (n + 2)/2 position=
s.</li></ul></li></ol> <h4 data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"h6">
      Advantages and Disadvantages of the Median
    </h4> <p data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"bottom-margins">
      The main advantage of the median is that=E2=80=94unlike the mean=E2=
=80=94it=E2=80=99s not skewed by extremely large or small values because th=
e median is based on the relative positions of the data points. This makes =
the measure helpful when examining skewed distributions=E2=80=94e.g., when =
calculating the ordinary income in a country because it=E2=80=99s not affec=
ted by a small number of extremely high or low-income outlier households.
    </p> <p data-v-60ddaa04=3D"">Let=E2=80=99s look at another example. Sup=
pose we estimate the median of these seven numbers: 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, and 1=
,000. The number of observations is odd and equals 7 (n=3D7). Therefore, th=
e median occupies the (n + 1)/2 =3D 8/2 =3D4th position and equals 5. Note =
that in this particular data set, the presence of an outlier (1,000) does n=
ot affect the median. Even if the eight observations were 10, the result wo=
uld be unchanged. But if we compute the arithmetic mean, the result would b=
e 146.7.</p> <p data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"formulas-overflow formulas-to=
p-down">
