    </p> <p data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"bottom-margins">
      Clearly, this value does not provide a good representation of the oth=
er six observations in the data set.
    </p> <p data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"bottom-margins">
      But the median also has its disadvantages. One is that the measure do=
es not consider all available information about the size and magnitude of t=
he observations and focuses only on their relative position. For example, t=
he median of 20, 50, 100, 120, and 130 is 100. We can replace observations =
20 and 50 with any values smaller than 100 and observations 120 and 130 wit=
h any two values greater than 100 without affecting the median value. (The =
median is insensitive to any values around the middle observation.)
    </p> <p data-v-60ddaa04=3D"">Obtaining the median is also more computat=
ionally complex. First, we need to sort the numbers in ascending or descend=
ing order, determine whether the sample size is odd or even, and apply one =
of two calculations. Using a median calculator eliminates this issue.</p></=
div> <div data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" id=3D"heading4" class=3D"article-section"><h=
3 data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"h4">
      What Is the Mode?
    </h3> <p data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"paragraph-one-advantages">
      The mode is the third important measure of central tendency=E2=80=94t=
he value that occurs most often in a distribution. For example, the mode in=
 the following data set [1, 4, 9, 5, 5, 5, 9, 3] is 5 because it occurs mos=
t often. Such a distribution is <span data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"bolded-=
texts">unimodal</span> because it has one value that occurs most often.
    </p> <p data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"paragraph-median-advantages">
      A distribution can have more than one mode or even no mode. For examp=
le, the mode in [2, 2, 3, 5, 5] equals 2 and 5 since both values appear twi=
ce each. In such a case, the dataset is <span data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D=
"bolded-texts">bimodal</span> because it has two modes.
    </p> <p data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"paragraph-median-advantages">
      Generally, a data set with more than two modes is <span data-v-60ddaa=
04=3D"" class=3D"bolded-texts">multimodal</span>. Now let=E2=80=99s examine=
 the following dataset [1,2,3,4,5]. All the values in the data set are diff=
erent, so no mode is available. In such cases, the mean or median are bette=
r alternatives.
    </p> <h4 data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"h6">
      Calculating the Mode
    </h4> <p data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"bottom-margins">
      In large datasets, using a calculator to find the mode will save you =
valuable time. But this is the easiest measure of central tendency to find =
manually=E2=80=94simply detect the most frequent value in a set.
    </p> <p data-v-60ddaa04=3D"">
      Sometimes when we explore continuous distributions [0.852=E2=80=A6,0.=
862=E2=80=A6,0.872=E2=80=A6.], we may not have a modal outcome since there =
are no two values that will be precisely the same. A common practice in suc=
h cases is to group data into intervals and explore which has the highest f=
requency=E2=80=94a practice in statistics known as finding the <span data-v=
-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"bolded-texts">modal interval</span>.
    </p> <h4 data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"steps h6">
      Steps for Calculating the Mode
    </h4> <p data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"bottom-margins">
      There are three steps for calculating the mode:
    </p> <ol data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"mean-median-mode-ol"><li data-v-=
60ddaa04=3D"">Place all numbers into ascending or descending order</li> <li=
 data-v-60ddaa04=3D"">Count how many times each value appears in the set</l=
i> <li data-v-60ddaa04=3D"">Check the one that appears the most. (This numb=
er is the mode.)</li></ol> <h4 data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"h6">
      Advantages and Disadvantages of the Mode
    </h4> <p data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"bottom-margins">
      The main advantage of the mode is that it=E2=80=99s not affected by e=
xtremely large or small values. Another advantage is that the measure is ea=
sy to understand and calculate. Moreover=E2=80=94unlike the mean and median=
=E2=80=94it can be used for both quantitative and qualitative data.
    </p> <p data-v-60ddaa04=3D"">But the measure also has disadvantages. As=
 mentioned previously, there are cases when it=E2=80=99s undefined because =
there are no repeats in the distribution. In addition, the mode is not base=
d on all the values in the dataset.</p></div> <div data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" id=
=3D"heading5" class=3D"article-section"><h3 data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"h=
4">
      Comparison of Mean, Median, and Mode
    </h3> <h4 data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"h6">
      Why Is Skewness Important?
    </h4> <p data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"bottom-margins"><a data-v-60ddaa=
04=3D"" href=3D"https://365datascience.com/tutorials/statistics-tutorials/s=
kewness-example/" target=3D"_blank">
        Skewness
      </a> tells us where the data is situated.
    </p> <p data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"paragraph-mean">
      The <span data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"bolded-texts">mean</span>, <s=
pan data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"bolded-texts">median</span> and <span dat=
a-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"bolded-texts">mode</span> should be used togethe=
r to understand the dataset better. <a data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" href=3D"https:/=
/www.wisdomjobs.com/e-university/research-methodology-tutorial-355/measures=
-of-asymmetry-skewness-11503.html" target=3D"_blank" class=3D"measure-asymm=
etry-a">Measures of asymmetry</a>, like <a data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" href=3D"htt=
ps://statisticscalculators.com/skewness-calculator" class=3D"" target=3D"_b=
lank">
        skewness
      </a>, are the link between central tendency measures and probability =
theory, which ultimately allows us to understand the data we=E2=80=99re wor=
king with.
    </p> <h4 data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"h6">
      When Will the Mean, Median, and Mode Be Equal?
    </h4> <p data-v-60ddaa04=3D"">The mean, median, and mode are equal when=
 the distribution is perfectly symmetrical and non-skewed. As the distribut=
ion becomes more skewed, the difference between the three measures differen=
t becomes larger.</p> <img data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" loading=3D"lazy" alt=3D"Med=
ian numbers when input is even." src=3D"https://statisticscalculators.com/_=
assets/images/mmm-04-desktop.png" class=3D"bigger-img"> <p data-v-60ddaa04=
=3D"">When we have right-skewed distribution, the mean is larger than the m=
edian, and the mode is the value with the highest visual representation.</p=
> <img data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" loading=3D"lazy" alt=3D"Positively Skewed graph=
." src=3D"https://statisticscalculators.com/_assets/images/mmm-05-desktop.p=
ng" class=3D"bigger-img"> <img data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" loading=3D"lazy" alt=3D=
"Negative Skewed graph." src=3D"https://statisticscalculators.com/_assets/i=
mages/mmm-06-desktop.png" class=3D"bigger-img"> <p data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" cla=
ss=3D"bottom-margin-40">
      In a negatively skewed frequency distribution, the mean is lower than=
 the median, and once again, the mode defines the highest point. Such a dis=
tribution is also called left skewed because the outliers are to the left.
    </p> <h4 data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"h6">
      Which Measure of Central Tendency is the Best?
    </h4> <p data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"bottom-margins-mean">
      The answer is simple. There is no best, but using only one is the wor=
st option. In other words, the three main measures are best used in combina=
tion with each other because they have complementary strengths and weakness=
es.
    </p> <p data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"paragraph-mean">
      The Mean, Median, and Mode Calculator generates all three measures of=
 central tendency simultaneously, streamlining your work.
    </p> <h4 data-v-60ddaa04=3D"" class=3D"h6">
